-- 
South African Stocks Decline, Led by Anglo American, BHP Billiton, Nedbank

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-04-12T15:55:05Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-12/south-african-stocks-decline-led-by-anglo-american-bhp-billiton-nedbank.html
The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index
fell the most since March 15, retreating 574.56, or 1.8 percent,
to 32,239.87 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , the diversified mining company
that makes up 11 percent of  South Africa ’s benchmark stock
index, retreated the most since May, dropping 16.69 rand, or 4.6
percent, to 348.81 rand. Copper slipped as much as 2.7 percent
to $9,593.25 a metric ton on the London Metal Exchange as  Japan 
raised its nuclear crisis rating to level 7, matching that of
Chernobyl.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s largest mining
company, slid 8.55 rand, or 3 percent, to 278.55 rand, the
biggest decline since March 10.  Nedbank Group Ltd. (NED)  , South Africa’s fourth-biggest
lender, slipped for the first time in six days, losing 4.01
rand, or 2.7 percent, to 147.50 rand. Citigroup Inc. reduced its
recommendation to “hold” from “buy.”  Palabora Mining Co. Ltd. (PAM SJ), a copper producer,
dropped the most in four weeks, falling 5.45 rand, or 3.7
percent, to 141.55 rand. The company said refined copper
production fell 15 percent in the quarter ended March, from the
previous quarter.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, dropped to the lowest intraday level in two
weeks, slipping 12.95 rand, or 3.4 percent, to 374 rand. Oil
fell for a second day because of concern that fuel demand will
slow, with the International Energy Agency warning that crude
prices above $100 a barrel are starting to hurt the global
economy.  Super Group Ltd. (SPG SJ), a transport services provider,
rose the most in two weeks, adding 2 cents, or 2.8 percent, to
73 cents. Super Group said it bought the remaining 28.5 percent
stake held by a minority shareholder in its Australian venture,
SG Fleet.  To contact the reporter on this story:
